<section xml:id="section-week1-activity">
  <title>Week 1 Activity</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-higher-dimensional-space">
    <title>higher-dimensional Space</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In 2-dimensional space, an infinitely long line divides the
          space into two pieces: one cannot pass from one side of the
          line to the other without crossing the line. In
          3-dimensional space, however, an infinitely long line does
          not do this; we can go around the line, and there isn't a
          division of space into two halves.
        </p>
        <p>
          In 3-dimensional space, an infinitely extended plane does
          divide space into two pieces, and it is impossible to pass
          from one side to the other without going across the plane.
          In 4-dimensional space, does an infinitely extended plane
          still divide it into two pieces, or can we go around it,
          like we go around the line in 3-dimensional space?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This is a tricky thing to try to visualize (being that
          4-dimensional space is not visualizable). However, we can
          argue by analogy. How do we get around the line in
          3-dimensions? We move to the side, then move past the line,
          instead of running into it. We can do this because we have
          two degrees of freedom in directions other than the direction
          of the line.
        </p>
        <p>
          The same thing works for a plane in 4-dimensional space.
          While in 3-dimensional space, we only have one dimension of
          movement apart from the plane. To get to the other side,
          moving in this one degree of freedom, we have to cross the
          plane. In 4-dimensional space, we have two other degrees of
          freedom. Like getting around the line in 3-dimensional
          space, we can move to the side, then move past the plane to
          reach <q>the other side.</q> There really isn't another
          side, much like a line in 3-dimensional space doesn't really
          create two sides of space. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
         In 2-dimensional space, a square or rectangle is enough to
         trap or contain something that lives in the plane. In
         3-dimensional space, a cube (or other box) is enough to trap
         or contain something. What do we need to contain something in
         4-dimensional space? In 5-dimensional space?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To contain something in 4-dimensional space, we need a 
          four-dimensional box. Since we have four independent and free
          directions of movement, we have to close of movement in all
          four of these directions. This box will have a front/back, a
          top/bottom, a left/right, and then an additional pair of
          sides which block in the fourth direction of movement. In
          five dimensional space, we need a five-dimensional box: it
          will have a front/back, top/bottom, left/right, and two
          other independent boundary pairs.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p> 
          In 2-dimensional space, the slices of a rectangle are lines.
          In 3-dimensional space, the slices of a box are rectangles.
          What are the slices of a 4-dimensional box? A 5-dimensional
          box?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          By a <q>slice,</q> it seems we are referring to a piece of
          the object of one smaller dimension. Therefore, the slices
          of this four-dimensional box must be three-dimensional
          boxes. In this way, we can think of a four-dimensional box
          as an infinite stack of three-dimensional boxes, all stacked
          in some new direction of movement. (The same way we can
          think of a cube as an infinite stack of squares moving in a
          direction perpendicular to the squares themselves).
          Likewise, the slices of a five-dimensional box are
          themselves four-dimensional boxes. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-vector-arithmetics">
    <title>Vector Arithmetic</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider these vectors.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              u \amp = \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{matrix} \right) 
              \amp 
              v \amp = \left( \begin{matrix} -2 \\ -1 \end{matrix} \right) 
              \amp 
              w \amp = \left( \begin{matrix} -3 \\ 2 \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Calculate and draw the following vectors. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp -u 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp -v 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp -w 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u+v
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u+w
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp v+w
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u-v
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp v-u
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u-w
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp w-u
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp v-w
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp w-v
            </mrow>
          </md>
          In addition, calcluate these lengths. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp |u|
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |v|
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |w|
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |u-v|
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |u-w|
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |v-w|
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We'll do the arithmetic one by one. Then, at the end, all
          the vector will be drawn in
          <xref ref="figure-vector-arithmetic" />.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp -u = - \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{matrix}
              \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} -3 \\ 0 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp -v = - \left( \begin{matrix} -2 \\ -1 \end{matrix}
              \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp -w = - \left( \begin{matrix} -3 \\ 2 \end{matrix}
              \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ -2 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u+v = \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{matrix}
              \right) + \left( \begin{matrix} -2 \\ -1 \end{matrix}
              \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} 1 \\ -1 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u+w = \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{matrix}
              \right) + \left( \begin{matrix} -3 \\ 2 \end{matrix}
              \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ 2 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp v+w = \left( \begin{matrix} -2 \\ - 1 \end{matrix}
              \right) + \left( \begin{matrix} -3 \\ 2 \end{matrix}
              \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} -5 \\ 1 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u-v = \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{matrix}
              \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} -2 \\ -1 \end{matrix}
              \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} 5 \\ 1 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp v-u = \left( \begin{matrix} -2 \\ -1 \end{matrix}
              \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{matrix}
              \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} -5 \\ -1 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u-w = \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{matrix}
              \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} -3 \\ 2 \end{matrix}
              \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} 6 \\ -2 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp w-u = \left( \begin{matrix} -3 \\ 2 \end{matrix}
              \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{matrix}
              \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} -6 \\ 2 \end{matrix}
              \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp v-w = \left( \begin{matrix} -2 \\ -1 \end{matrix}
              \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} -3 \\ 2 \end{matrix}
              \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} 1 \\ -3 \end{matrix}
              \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp w-v = \left( \begin{matrix} -3 \\ 2 \end{matrix}
              \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} -2 \\ -1 \end{matrix}
              \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          <figure xml:id="figure-vector-arithmetic">
            <caption>Vector Arithmetic</caption>
            <image width="80%" source="images/figure10" />
              size(12cm,8cm);
              import graph;

              xlimits(-7,7);
              ylimits(-4,4);

              xaxis("$x$",Ticks("%"));
              yaxis("$y$",Ticks("%"));

              draw((0,0)--(3,0),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(-2,-1),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(-3,2),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(-3,0),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(2,1),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(3,-2),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(1,-1),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(0,2),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(-5,1),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(5,1),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(-5,-1),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(6,-2),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(-6,2),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(1,-3),Arrow); 
              draw((0,0)--(-1,3),Arrow); 
              
              draw((3,0)--(5,3),dotted);
              draw((1,-1)--(5,-4),dotted);
              draw((-3,0)--(-5,-3),dotted);
              draw((0,2)--(0.5,3),dotted);
              
              label("$u$",(5,3),E);
              label("$v$",(-2,-1),SW);
              label("$w$",(-3,2),NW);
              label("$-u$",(-6,-3),SE);
              label("$-v$",(2,1),NE);
              label("$-w$",(3,-2),SE);
              label("$u+v$",(5,-4),E);
              label("$u+w$",(0.5,3),E);
              label("$v+w$",(-5,1),W);
              label("$u-v$",(5,1),E);
              label("$v-u$",(-5,-1),W);
              label("$u-w$",(6,-2),E);
              label("$w-u$",(-6,2),W);
              label("$v-w$",(1.8,-3),S);
              label("$w-v$",(-1,3),NW);
          </figure>
          In addition, calcluate these lengths. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp |u| = \sqrt{3^2 + 0^2} = \sqrt{9} = 3 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |v| = \sqrt{(-2)^2 + (-1)^2} = \sqrt{5} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |w| = \sqrt{(-3)^2 + 2^2} = \sqrt{13} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |u-v| = \sqrt{5^2 + 1^2} = \sqrt{26} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |u-w| = \sqrt{6^2 + (-2)^2} = \sqrt{40} = 2
              \sqrt{10} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |v-w| = \sqrt{1^2 + (-3)^2} = \sqrt{10} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider these vectors.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              u \amp = \left( \begin{matrix} 6 \\ 0 \\ -1 \\ -1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \amp 
              v \amp = \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ -3 \\ 1 \\ -3 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) 
              \amp 
              w \amp = \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ -1 \\ 0 \\ 3 \\ 5
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Calculate the following vectors and length. (Since this is
          in <m>\RR^5</m>, drawing these is no longer an option. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp -u 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp -v 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp -w 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u+v
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u+w
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp v+w
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u-v
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp v-u
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u-w
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp w-u
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp v-w
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp w-v
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |u|
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |v|
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |w|
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |u-v|
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |u-w|
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |v-w|
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We'll do the calculation one by one. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp -u = - \left( \begin{matrix} 6 \\ 0 \\ -1 \\ -1 \\
              1 \end{matrix} \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} -6 \\ 0
              \\ 1 \\ 1 \\ -1 \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp -v = - \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ -3 \\ 1 \\ -3 \\
              1 \end{matrix} \right) \left( \begin{matrix} -3 \\ 3 \\
              -1 \\ 3 \\ -1 \end{matrix} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp -w = - \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ -1 \\ 0 \\ 3 \\ 5
              \end{matrix} \right) = \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0
              \\ -3 \\ -5 \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u+v = \left( \begin{matrix} 6 \\ 0 \\ -1 \\ -1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) + \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ -3 \\
              1 \\ -3 \\ 1 \end{matrix} \right) = \left(
              \begin{matrix} 9 \\ -3 \\ 0 \\ -4 \\ 2 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u+w = \left( \begin{matrix} 6 \\ 0 \\ -1 \\ -1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) + \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ -1 \\
              0 \\ 3 \\ 5 \end{matrix} \right) = \left( \begin{matrix}
              6 \\ -1 \\ -1 \\ 2 \\ 6 \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp v+w = \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ -3 \\ 1 \\ -3 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) + \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ -1 \\
              0 \\ 3 \\ 5 \end{matrix} \right) = \left( \begin{matrix}
              3 \\ -4 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 6 \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u-v = \left( \begin{matrix} 6 \\ 0 \\ -1 \\ -1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ -3 \\
              1 \\ -3 \\ 1 \end{matrix} \right) = \left(
              \begin{matrix} 3 \\ 3 \\ -2 \\ 2 \\ 0 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp v-u = \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ -3 \\ 1 \\ -3 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} 6 \\ 0 \\
              -1 \\ -1 \\ 1 \end{matrix} \right) + \left(
              \begin{matrix} -3 \\ -3 \\ 2 \\ -2 \\ 0 \end{matrix}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp u-w = \left( \begin{matrix} 6 \\ 0 \\ -1 \\ -1 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ -1 \\
              0 \\ 3 \\ 5 \end{matrix} \right) + \left( \begin{matrix}
              6 \\ 1 \\ -1 \\ -4 \\ -4 \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp w-u = \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ -1 \\ 0 \\ 3 \\ 5
              \end{matrix} \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} 6 \\ 0 \\
              -1 \\ -1 \\ 1 \end{matrix} \right) + \left(
              \begin{matrix} -6 \\ -1 \\ 1 \\ 4 \\ 4 \end{matrix}
              \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp v-w = \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ -3 \\ 1 \\ -3 \\ 1
              \end{matrix} \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ -1 \\
              0 \\ 3 \\ 5 \end{matrix} \right) + \left( \begin{matrix}
              3 \\ -2 \\ 1 \\ -6 \\ -4 \end{matrix} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp w-v = 
              \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ -1 \\ 0 \\ 3 \\ 5
              \end{matrix} \right) - 
              \left( \begin{matrix} 3 \\ -3 \\ 1 \\ -3 \\ 1 
              \end{matrix} \right) +
              \left( \begin{matrix} -3 \\ 2 \\ -1 \\ 6 \\ 4
              \end{matrix} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |u| = \sqrt{6^2 + 0^2 + (-1)^2 + (-1)^2 + 1^2} =
              \sqrt{39} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |v| = \sqrt{3^2 + (-3)^2 + 1^2 + (-3)^2 + 1^2} =
              \sqrt{29} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |w| = \sqrt{0^2 + (-1)^2 + 0^2 + 3^2 + 5^2} =
              \sqrt{35} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |u-v| = \sqrt{3^2 + 3^2 + (-2)^2 + 2^2 + 0^2} =
              \sqrt{26} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |u-w| = \sqrt{6^2 + 1^2 + (-1)^2 + (-4)^2 + (-4)^2} =
              \sqrt{70} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp |v-w| = \sqrt{3^2 + (-2)^2 + 1^2 + (-6)^2 + (-4)^2}
              = \sqrt{66} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-week1-proofs">
    <title>Proof Questions</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>a \in \RR</m> and <m>u \in \RR^3</m>, prove that <m>|au|
          = |a||u|</m>. (Use the definition of scalar multiplication
          and the definition of length of a vector. Start with the
          left side and try to turn it into the right or vice-versa.
          Do not reduce both equations to equivalent expressions --
          that's not a valid proof technique. You may try
          some examples out if you wish, but your final solution
          should be general. Finally, note that the notation here is a
          bit subtle: <m>|au|</m> and <m>|u|</m> are the lengths of
          vectors, defined by Pythagorean calculations, but <m>|a|</m>
          is just the absolute value of a real number.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I will start with the left side and try to manipulate it
          into the right side. I'll write <m>u</m> in components and
          use the definition of the scalar multiplication to start.
          <me>
            |au| = \left| a \left( \begin{matrix} u_1 \\ u_2 \\ u_3
            \end{matrix} \right) \right| = \left| \left(
            \begin{matrix} au_1 \\ au_2 \\ au_3 \end{matrix} \right)
            \right|
          </me>
          This is the definition of scalar multiplication: multiply
          the scalar by each component of the vector. Now I use the
          square root definition of the length of a vector. 
          <me>
            \left| \left( \begin{matrix} au_1 \\ au_2 \\ au_3
            \end{matrix} \right) \right| = \sqrt{(au_1)^2 + (au_2)^2 +
            (au_3)^2} 
          </me>
          Now I need to do some algebra with the square root. I can
          distribute the exponent, using the exponent rule <m>(xy)^a =
          x^ay^2</m>.
          <me>
            \sqrt{(au_1)^2 + (au_2)^2 + (au_3)^2} = \sqrt{a^2 u_1^2 +
            a^2 u_2^2 + a_2u_3^2}
          </me>
          Now I can factor out the <m>a^2</m>. Once it is factored out,
          I can also remove it from the square root. 
          <me>
            \sqrt{a^2 u_1^2 + a^2 u_2^2 + a_2u_3^2} = \sqrt{a^2(u_1^2
            + u_2^2 + u_3^2)} = |a| \sqrt{u_1^2 + u_2^2 + u_3^2}
          </me>
          When I take <m>a^2</m> out of the square root, since the
          square root also returns a positive number, I don't get
          <m>a</m> back. If <m>a</m> was negative to start, then I will
          have turned <m>a</m> from negative to positive. Therefore, I get
          the absolute value of <m>a</m> back. Finally, I can recognize
          the remaining term as the definition of the length of a
          vector. 
          <me>
            |a| \sqrt{u_1^2 + u_2^2 + u_3^2} = |a| |u| 
          </me>
        </p>
        Now I have started with the left side and produced the right.
        This proves that <m>|au| = |a||u|</m>, as desired. 
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> are vectors in <m>\RR^3</m>, prove
          that <m>|u-v| = |v-u|</m>. Then adapt your argument to work
          for vectors in <m>\RR^n</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We will write <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> in components, take
          their difference and then apply the length operation. I will
          start with the left side and try to produce the right. 
          <me>
            |u-v| = \left| \left( \begin{matrix} u_1 \\ u_2 \\ u_3
            \end{matrix} \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\
            v_3 \end{matrix} \right) \right|
          </me>
          The difference is done componentwise. 
          <me>
            \left| \left( \begin{matrix} u_1 \\ u_2 \\ u_3
            \end{matrix} \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\
            v_3 \end{matrix} \right) \right| = 
            \left| \left( \begin{matrix} u_1 - v_1 \\ u_2 - v_2 \\ u_3
            - v_3 \end{matrix} \right) \right| 
          </me>
          Then we use the square root definition of the length.
          <me>
            \left| \left( \begin{matrix} u_1 - v_1 \\ u_2 - v_2 \\ u_3
            - v_3 \end{matrix} \right) \right| = \sqrt{(u_1-v_1)^2 +
            (u_2-v_2)^2 + (u_3-v_3)^2}
          </me>
          Now, each of the three terms is square. Since they are
          square, any positive or negative will become positive since
          squares are always positive. Therefore, we could multiply by
          <m>(-1)</m> inside the square root to no effect. This
          will interchange the order of the difference in each term.
          <me>
            \sqrt{(u_1-v_1)^2 + (u_2-v_2)^2 + (u_3-v_3)^2} = 
            \sqrt{(v_1-u_1)^2 + (v_2-u_2)^2 + (v_3-u_3)^2} 
          </me>
          Then we repeat the steps from before in reverse. This is the
          definition of the length of a vector with the terms in the
          squares as components. 
          <me>
            \sqrt{(v_1-u_1)^2 + (v_2-u_2)^2 + (v_3-u_3)^2} = \left|
            \left( \begin{matrix} v_1 - u_1 \\ v_2 - u_2 \\ v_3 - u_3 
            \end{matrix} \right) \right|
          </me>
          Since each term is a difference, we can write this as the
          difference of two vectors. 
          <me>
            \left| \left( \begin{matrix} v_1 - u_1 \\ v_2 - u_2 \\ v_3
            - u_3 \end{matrix} \right) \right| = \left| \left(
            \begin{matrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\ v_3 \end{matrix} \right) -
            \left( \begin{matrix} u_1 \\ u_2 \\ u_3 \end{matrix}
            \right) \right| 
          </me>
          Finally, these are just the component of the vectors
          <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>. 
          <me>
            = \left| \left( \begin{matrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\ v_3
            \end{matrix} \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} u_1 \\ u_2 \\
            u_3 \end{matrix} \right) \right| = |v-u|
          </me>
          We have started from the left and produced the right in a
          string of equality, so we have proven the desired result. 
        </p>
        <p>
          If we wanted to adapt this to a more general proof for
          <m>\RR^n</m>, the steps of the proof would be identical, but
          we would have vectors with <m>n</m> components instead of
          just three components. We would use ellipses to indicate the
          list of components. The proof would start like this.
          <me>
            |u-v| = \left| \left( \begin{matrix} u_1 \\ u_2 \\ \vdots
            \\ u_n \end{matrix} \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} v_1 \\
            v_2 \\ \\ \vdots \\ v_n \end{matrix} \right) \right|
          </me>
          The difference is done componentwise. 
          <me>
            \left| \left( \begin{matrix} u_1 \\ u_2 \\\vdots \\  u_n
            \end{matrix} \right) - \left( \begin{matrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\
            \vdots \\ v_n \end{matrix} \right) \right| = 
            \left| \left( \begin{matrix} u_1 - v_1 \\ u_2 - v_2 \\
            \vdots \\ u_n - v_n \end{matrix} \right) \right| 
          </me>
          I won't repeat all the steps, but they would proceed exactly
          in the same sequence as before, resulting in <m>|v-u|</m>
          eventually at the end. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that the zero vector is the <em>only</em> vector in 
          <m>\RR^n</m> of length zero. (To prove that it is the only
          vector with this property, assume that <m>u \in \RR^n</m> is
          a vector with length zero and prove that <m>u</m> must be the
          zero vector. This will show that the zero vector is the
          only vector with the desired property). 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let <m>u</m> be an arbitrary vector in <m>\RR^n</m> of
          length 0. We will start by writing <m>u</m> in components and
          use the definition of length. Note we need ellipses to show
          all the components of <m>u</m>, since we are working in an
          arbitrary dimension <m>n</m>. 
          <me>
            |u| = \left| \left( \begin{matrix} u_1 \\ u_2 \\ \vdots \\
            u_n \end{matrix} \right) \right|
          </me>
          Then we use the definition of length. By assumption, we set
          this length equal to zero. 
          <me>
            |u| = \sqrt{(u_1)^2 + (u_2)^2 + \ldots + (u_n)^2} = 0 
          </me>
          We can square both sides of the equation.
          <me>
            (\sqrt{(u_1)^2 + (u_2)^2 + \ldots + (u_n)^2})^2 = 0^2 
          </me>
          The square root and squaring cancel each other out. 
          <me>
            (u_1)^2 + (u_2)^2 + \ldots + (u_n)^2 = 0
          </me>
          On the left, we have the sum of a bunch of non-negative
          numbers (since the square of any real number must be zero or
          postive). On the right we have zero. The only way that a
          bunch of non-negative numbers add up to zero is if they are
          all zero to begin with. Therefore, we see that for each
          index <m>i</m>, the component <m>u_i</m> must be zero. But
          that means that 
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix} u_1 \\ u_2 \\ \vdots \\ u_n 
            \end{matrix} \right) =
            \left( \begin{matrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ \vdots \\ 0 
            \end{matrix} \right)
          </me>
          This is precisely the definition of the zero vector: the
          vector where all components are zero. Therefore, <m>u</m>
          must be the zero vector. To conclude, we assumed that
          <m>u</m> had length zero and thus concluded that it must be the
          zero vector. This proved that the zero vector is the only
          vector with length zero. 
        </p>
      </solution>
